# 54_actions_zorder_smoke — Tier 2 m4 Z-order sweep (s255).
# Validates the four Z-order arrange actions migrated from raw
# `add_action` to `add_scripted_action`: arrange-bring-front /
# arrange-bring-forward / arrange-send-backward / arrange-send-back.
# Sibling smoke to 52 / 53, same conservative-shape posture: verb-
# presence + invocation-no-throw + refusal coverage.
#
# **Why conservative.** None of the four arrange verbs has a scriptable
# observable today. Z-order is a property of the scene-graph child
# ordering; `objects` doesn't expose per-object z-index, and the
# operation itself acts on selection (not a named target). Adding a
# z-index observable to `objects` is m3+-of-objects territory, separate
# from the wrap-now sweep. Trace channel: invocations land cleanly.
# Visual channel: Scott confirms menu Object ▸ Arrange ▸ Bring to Front
# / Bring Forward / Send Backward / Send to Back (and any hotkeys
# bound) still reorder the selection identically.
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Seven observables across the wrapper-side surface:
#
#   Phase 1: `list` — confirm `win` is still registered. Same sanity-
#            check pattern as 52 / 53.
#
#   Phases 2-5: each of the four arrange verbs invoked once. Operator-
#            visual on each `ok` echo. Negative case: any
#            `error invoke threw: win arrange-<x>: unknown verb` means
#            the helper's register_action() never landed for that verb.
#
#            Each invoke fires m_canvas.arrange(Canvas::ArrangeOp::X)
#            on the current selection. With a multi-object selection,
#            the visual effect is reordering in the scene tree (front-
#            most object draws last; back-most draws first). With a
#            single-object selection in a layer that only holds one
#            object, all four verbs are no-ops at the visible level
#            but still fire cleanly at the wrapper.
#
#   Phases 6-7: refusal coverage, parallel to 52 / 53. Unknown-verb
#            and extra-argument refusals. Re-exercised per Tier 2
#            smoke to prevent drift.
#
# ── Caller context ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Runs through ScripterWindow's listener, m_context = RunContext::Scripter.
# All four m4-batch verbs declare their mask as Scripter | TestRunner
# per the wrap-now posture. Macro is OUT — same posture as m3.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke MUTATES scene-graph child ordering via the four arrange
# verbs. The mutations, applied to whatever the current selection is:
#
#   - `win arrange-bring-front`   — selection moves to the end of its
#                                   parent's children list (front).
#   - `win arrange-bring-forward` — selection swaps with the next-front
#                                   sibling (one step toward front).
#   - `win arrange-send-backward` — selection swaps with the next-back
#                                   sibling (one step toward back).
#   - `win arrange-send-back`     — selection moves to the start of its
#                                   parent's children list (back).
#
# Net effect of front → forward → backward → back on the same
# selection: depends on how many siblings exist. With ≥3 siblings,
# the selection moves to back AND ends up at the back of the list.
# With 2 siblings, it ends up at the back. With 1 sibling (or zero),
# all four ops are no-ops at the visible level.
#
# After the smoke runs:
#   - The selection is at the back of its parent's children list
#     (assuming the sequence ran on a multi-sibling parent). Scott
#     may want to ⌘Z four times to restore exact pre-run order, or
#     Bring to Front manually.
#   - No content added / removed / edited; only ordering.
#
# Safe to run repeatedly. Not idempotent — see m3 smoke's note on
# the side-effecting Tier 2 smoke convention.
#
# ── Precondition reminders ────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke assumes:
#   1. Curvz is running with at least one project + one document open.
#   2. The active doc has at least one object selected. The arrange
#      operations no-op cleanly on empty selection (the action wrapper
#      doesn't refuse; the canvas-side handler does nothing), so the
#      trace channel passes either way — but the visual channel needs
#      a selection (ideally in a layer with ≥2 objects) to confirm.

#[sub] === Phase 1: registry sanity-check — `win` is still registered ===

#[sub] Re-confirms the m2/m3 plumbing didn't regress.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: arrange-bring-front verb is addressable ===

#[sub] First m4-batch verb. Invoke; no error means the helper
#[sub] registered the action. Calls m_canvas.arrange(BringToFront);
#[sub] visual: selection draws on top of all its siblings.

win arrange-bring-front

#[sub] === Phase 3: arrange-bring-forward verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Second m4-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.arrange(BringForward);
#[sub] visual: selection swaps with the next-front sibling.
#[sub] (After phase 2's bring-front, selection is already at front,
#[sub] so this is a no-op at the visible level. Wrapper-side still
#[sub] fires cleanly.)

win arrange-bring-forward

#[sub] === Phase 4: arrange-send-backward verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Third m4-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.arrange(SendBackward);
#[sub] visual: selection swaps with the next-back sibling (one step
#[sub] back from the front position phase 2 left it at).

win arrange-send-backward

#[sub] === Phase 5: arrange-send-back verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Fourth and final m4-batch verb. Calls
#[sub] m_canvas.arrange(SendToBack); visual: selection moves to the
#[sub] back of its parent's children list.

win arrange-send-back

#[sub] === Phase 6: unknown-verb refusal ===

#[sub] Same refusal smoke as 52 phase 7 / 53 phase 8. `win quit`
#[sub] remains the canonical bucket-C unknown-verb test target.

win quit

#[sub] === Phase 7: extra-argument refusal ===

#[sub] Parallel to 52 phase 8 / 53 phase 9. Use one of the new
#[sub] m4 verbs — `win arrange-bring-front "argument"` — exercises
#[sub] the invoke() body's args-empty check on a new verb.

win arrange-bring-front "argument"

